meta.description: The cream white. Balanced, with stable aesthetics. The first mural ‘Velvet’ shade.
The iron grey. Soft, warm, expressive. The darkest shade of 1931.
The medium grey. Elegant and restrained. It can place the walls into shadow.
The discreet grey. Natural, neutral, discreetly calm. The second ‘Velvet’ shade.
The pearl grey. Weakly luminescent and airy. The third mural ‘Velvet’ shade.
The luminous ultramarin. Dynamic, imposing and much in demand.
The lucent sky blue. Like the sky on a clear, sunny day in summer.
The brightened ultramarine. A space atmosphere that loosens up. The first ‘Space’ shade.
The light ultramarine. An atmosphere that recedes gently. The second ‘Space’ shade.
The blue grey. The imagination. A restrained atmosphere. The third ‘Space’ shade.
The powerful cerulean. Appears dynamic and attracts the attention.
The luminous cerulean. Warm, sensual, Mediterranean. The colour tends towards the observer.
The summery sky. Static, does not come forward anymore. The first mural ‘Sky’ shade.
The sky reflected in the water. Subordinates itself. The second mural ‘Sky’ shade.
The sky reflected in ocean waves. Somewhat greenish. The third mural ‘Sky’ colour shade.
The english green. Reminds of aristocracy, also of freshness of the forest.
The slightly greyed english green. Like a discreet Verona green.
The mild grey green. The colour shade links retentively to the landscape.
The rich brilliant green. A deep and very neutral green; expressing the summer.
The vernal green. Very expressive. The first tone of the ‘Scenery’ atmosphere.
The green of spring. Natural and fruitful. The second shade representing ‘Scenery’.
The pale green. Gentle, smooth and balanced. The third tone with the mural value of ‘Scenery’.
The natural sand. Restrained and very elegant. The first tone with mural value of ‘Sand’.
The shiny orange. A dynamic, youthful and optimistic colour.
The orange apricot. A dynamic, touching and consistently attractive ton.
The sandy orange. Earthy, gentle and constructive. The second mural ‘Sand’ colour.
The deep dynamic red. Or the luminescent vermilion red.
The gentle pink. Earthy, warm and restrained. The first shade with ‘Masonry’ significance.
The noble carmine red. Steeped in history, dignified and brilliant.
The artistic red. The tradition-rich red of famous painters.
The bright pink. Or the medium dynamic rose.
The red of ancient architecture. An earthy and deeply luminescent nuance.
The medium Terracotta. An earthy and warm tone, which emphasises comfort.
The bright red ochre. Earthy and stable. The second shade with ‘Masonry’ significance.
The deeply burnt sienna. It fixes the wall impressively.
The light brick red. Suited for timeless colour combinations.
The colour of the summery masonry. Loamy and soft. The third ‘Masonry’ shade.
The pale sienna. A sandy, discreet and stable colour shade.
The marron. Deeply red brown, burnt. Like a chestnut.
The burnt umber. An ideal background colour. The third shade with mural value of ‘Sand’.
The dark natural umber. An elegant brown grey colour.
The grey brown natural umber. A balanced, aesthetic and appealing colour.
The discrete natural umber. As shadow colour, ideal for combinations.
The cinnabar red. A fiery shade which catches the eye and reduces the space.
The ivory white. Elegant, charming, chalky. The calm background colour.
The luminous pink. Less earthy and mostly used as complement to other luscious colours.
The deep brown sienna. A burnt, rich, dynamic and stable colour tone.
The ivory black. Black as the night. Le Corbusier’s only, impressive black tone.
The olive green. Green yellow or yellow green? A unique classic.
The emerald green. A dynamic shade with luminous power.
The dynamic medium grey. It reacts stable and dynamic in any light.
The dark burnt umber. Resembles mahogany. It can camouflage and hide.
The spectacular ultramarine. An impressive colour shade which moves worlds.
The golden ochre. A deep, powerful and very present colour tone.
The ruby. It is darksome and shining, velvety, festive and luxurious.
Represents sky and sea. The colour shade is virtually infinitely combinable.
The grey in the morning. Somewhat cool. The shade is receding in contrast to white.
The natural sienna ochre. Earthy, warm and softer than yellow.
The deeply dark natural umber. Camouflaging, emphasising other colours.
The powerful orange. Saturated and energetic. It steps forward and unfolds bold effects.
The profound ultramarine blue. A fascinating shade which reflects infinity.
The dark grey. Strong, rich and close to a metallic effect.
The yellow colour of the sun. It shines impressively in good light.
